    <h2>Data Sources</h2>
    <p>The pipeline ingests data from four primary sources:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>IEA</strong> — monthly energy supply, production, and consumption data by country and fuel type</li>
      <li><strong>World Bank API</strong> — macroeconomic indicators including GDP growth, inflation, and commodity price indices</li>
      <li><strong>UN Comtrade</strong> — bilateral trade flows for energy commodities, used to map supply chain dependencies</li>
      <li><strong>Our World in Data / BP Statistical Review</strong> — long-run historical price series and energy mix data for context and baseline modelling</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Approach</h2>
    <h3>Signal Design</h3>
    <p>
      The core hypothesis is that geopolitical disruptions leave detectable footprints in trade
      flow data (UN Comtrade) and supply figures (IEA) before they fully propagate to consumer
      prices. The pipeline calculates a set of "disruption signals" — deviations from rolling
      baselines across key producer-exporter pairs.
    </p>

    <h3>Modelling Strategy</h3>
    <p>
      The plan is to compare a baseline ARIMA/SARIMA model (price series only) against an
      augmented model (ARIMAX or gradient-boosted) that incorporates the disruption signals
      as exogenous features. The evaluation metric will be directional accuracy on shock
      detection, not just RMSE — because being right about the direction matters more than
      precise magnitude for the target use case.
    </p>

